# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: admet-prediction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:admet-prediction/adme] ADME describes the disposition of a pharmaceutical compound within an organism.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] The four criteria all influence the drug levels and kinetics of drug exposure to the tissues and hence influence the performance and pharmacological activity of the compound as a drug.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Sometimes liberation and/or toxicity are also considered, yielding LADME, ADMET, or LADMET.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] For a compound to reach a tissue, it usually must be taken into the bloodstream – often via mucous surfaces like the digestive tract (intestinal absorption) – before being taken up by the target cells.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Factors such as poor compound solubility, gastric emptying time, intestinal transit time, chemical instability in the stomach, and inability to permeate the intestinal wall can all reduce the extent to which a drug is absorbed after oral administration.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Absorption critically determines the compound's bioavailability.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Drugs that absorb poorly when taken orally must be administered in some less desirable way, like intravenously or by inhalation (e.g. zanamivir).
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Routes of administration are an important consideration.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] The compound needs to be carried to its effector site, most often via the bloodstream.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] From there, the compound may distribute into muscle and organs, usually to differing extents.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] After entry into the systemic circulation, either by intravascular injection or by absorption from any of the various extracellular sites, the drug is subjected to numerous distribution processes that tend to lower its plasma concentration.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Distribution is defined as the reversible transfer of a drug between one compartment to another.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Some factors affecting drug distribution include regional blood flow rates, molecular size, polarity and binding to serum proteins, forming a complex.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Distribution can be a serious problem at some natural barriers like the blood–brain barrier.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Compounds begin to break down as soon as they enter the body.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] The majority of small-molecule drug metabolism is carried out in the liver by redox enzymes, termed cytochrome P450 enzymes.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] As metabolism occurs, the initial (parent) compound is converted to new compounds called metabolites.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] When metabolites are pharmacologically inert, metabolism deactivates the administered dose of parent drug and this usually reduces the effects on the body.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Metabolites may also be pharmacologically active, sometimes more so than the parent drug (see prodrug).
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Compounds and their metabolites need to be removed from the body via excretion, usually through the kidneys (urine) or in the feces.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Unless excretion is complete, accumulation of foreign substances can adversely affect normal metabolism.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] There are three main sites where drug excretion occurs.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] The kidney is the most important site and it is where products are excreted through urine.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Biliary excretion or fecal excretion is the process that initiates in the liver and passes through to the gut until the products are finally excreted along with waste products or feces.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] The last main method of excretion is through the lungs (e.g. anesthetic gases).
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Sometimes, the potential or real toxicity of the compound is taken into account (**ADME-Tox** or **ADMET**).
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Parameters used to characterize toxicity include the median lethal dose (LD50) and therapeutic index.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] Computational chemists try to predict the ADME-Tox qualities of compounds through methods like QSPR or QSAR.
[src:admet-prediction/adme] The route of administration critically influences ADME.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] In pharmacology, **bioavailability** is a subcategory of absorption and is the fraction (%) of an administered drug that reaches the systemic circulation.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] By definition, when a medication is administered intravenously, its bioavailability is 100%.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] However, when a medication is administered via routes other than intravenous, its bioavailability is lower due to intestinal epithelium absorption and first-pass metabolism.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Thereby, mathematically, bioavailability equals the ratio of comparing the area under the plasma drug concentration curve versus time (AUC) for the extravascular formulation to the AUC for the intravascular formulation.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] AUC is used because AUC is proportional to the dose that has entered the systemic circulation.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Bioavailability of a drug is an average value; to take population variability into account, deviation range is shown as ±.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] To ensure that the drug taker who has poor absorption is dosed appropriately, the bottom value of the deviation range is employed to represent real bioavailability and to calculate the drug dose needed for the drug taker to achieve systemic concentrations similar to the intravenous formulation.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] To dose without knowing the drug taker's absorption rate, the bottom value of the deviation range is used in order to ensure the intended efficacy, unless the drug is associated with a narrow therapeutic window.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] For dietary supplements, herbs and other nutrients in which the route of administration is nearly always oral, bioavailability generally designates simply the quantity or fraction of the ingested dose that is absorbed.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Bioavailability is a term used to describe the percentage of an administered dose of a xenobiotic that reaches the systemic circulation.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] It is denoted by the letter *f* (or, if expressed in percent, by *F*).
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] In nutritional science, which covers the intake of nutrients and non-drug dietary ingredients, the concept of bioavailability lacks the well-defined standards associated with the pharmaceutical industry.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] The pharmacological definition cannot apply to these substances because utilization and absorption is a function of the nutritional status and physiological state of the subject, resulting in even greater differences from individual to individual (inter-individual variation).
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Therefore, bioavailability for dietary supplements can be defined as the proportion of the administered substance capable of being absorbed and available for use or storage.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] In both pharmacology and nutrition sciences, bioavailability is measured by calculating the area under curve (AUC) of the drug concentration time profile.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] It is the fraction of exposure to a drug (AUC) through non-intravenous administration compared with the corresponding intravenous administration of the same drug.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] The comparison must be dose normalized (e.g., account for different doses or varying weights of the subjects); consequently, the amount absorbed is corrected by dividing the corresponding dose administered.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] In pharmacology, in order to determine absolute bioavailability of a drug, a pharmacokinetic study must be done to obtain a *plasma drug concentration vs time* plot for the drug after both intravenous (iv) and extravascular (non-intravenous, i.e., oral) administration.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] The absolute bioavailability is the dose-corrected area under curve (*AUC*) non-intravenous divided by *AUC* intravenous.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] The formula for calculating the absolute bioavailability, *F*, of a drug administered orally (po) is given below (where *D* is dose administered).
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Therefore, a drug given by the intravenous route will have an absolute bioavailability of 100% (*f* = 1), whereas drugs given by other routes usually have an absolute bioavailability of *less* than one.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] If we compare the two different dosage forms having same active ingredients and compare the two drug bioavailability is called comparative bioavailability.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Although knowing the true extent of systemic absorption (referred to as absolute bioavailability) is clearly useful, in practice it is not determined as frequently as one may think.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] The reason for this is that its assessment requires an *intravenous reference*; that is, a route of administration that guarantees all of the administered drug reaches systemic circulation.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Such studies come at considerable cost, not least of which is the necessity to conduct preclinical toxicity tests to ensure adequate safety, as well as potential problems due to solubility limitations.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] The intravenous and oral concentrations can then be deconvoluted by virtue of their different isotopic constitution, and can thus be used to determine the oral and intravenous pharmacokinetics from the same dose administration.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] This technique eliminates pharmacokinetic issues with non-equivalent clearance as well as enabling the intravenous dose to be administered with a minimum of toxicology and formulation.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] The technique was first applied using stable-isotopes such as 13C and mass-spectrometry to distinguish the isotopes by mass difference.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] More recently, 14C labelled drugs are administered intravenously and accelerator mass spectrometry (AMS) used to measure the isotopically labelled drug along with mass spectrometry for the unlabelled drug.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] In all such cases, to conduct an absolute bioavailability study requires that the drug be given intravenously.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Intravenous administration of a developmental drug can provide valuable information on the fundamental pharmacokinetic parameters of volume of distribution (*V*) and clearance (*CL*).
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] In pharmacology, relative bioavailability measures the bioavailability (estimated as the *AUC*) of a formulation (A) of a certain drug when compared with another formulation (B) of the same drug, usually an established standard, or through administration via a different route.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] When the standard consists of intravenously administered drug, this is known as absolute bioavailability (see above).
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Relative bioavailability is one of the measures used to assess bioequivalence (*BE*) between two drug products.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] For FDA approval, a generic manufacturer must demonstrate that the 90% confidence interval for the ratio of the mean responses (usually of *AUC* and the maximum concentration, *C*max) of its product to that of the "brand name drug" is within the limits of 80% to 125%.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Where *AUC* refers to the concentration of the drug in the blood over time *t* = 0 to *t* = ∞, *C*max refers to the maximum concentration of the drug in the blood.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] When *T*max is given, it refers to the time it takes for a drug to reach *C*max.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] While the mechanisms by which a formulation affects bioavailability and bioequivalence have been extensively studied in drugs, formulation factors that influence bioavailability and bioequivalence in nutritional supplements are largely unknown.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] As a result, in nutritional sciences, relative bioavailability or bioequivalence is the most common measure of bioavailability, comparing the bioavailability of one formulation of the same dietary ingredient to another.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] The absolute bioavailability of a drug, when administered by an extravascular route, is usually less than one (i.e., *F*< 100%).
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Various physiological factors reduce the availability of drugs prior to their entry into the systemic circulation.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Whether a drug is taken with or without food will also affect absorption, other drugs taken concurrently may alter absorption and first-pass metabolism, intestinal motility alters the dissolution of the drug and may affect the degree of chemical degradation of the drug by intestinal microflora.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Disease states affecting liver metabolism or gastrointestinal function will also have an effect.
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] Each of these factors may vary from patient to patient (inter-individual variation), and indeed in the same patient over time (intra-individual variation).
[src:admet-prediction/bioavailability] In clinical trials, inter-individual variation is a critical measurement used to assess the bioavailability differences from patient to patient in order to ensure predictable dosing.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The **blood–brain barrier** (**BBB**) is a highly selective semipermeable border of endothelial cells that regulates the transfer of solutes and chemicals between the circulatory system and the central nervous system, thus protecting the brain from harmful or unwanted substances in the blood.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The blood–brain barrier is formed by endothelial cells of the capillary wall, astrocyte end-feet ensheathing the capillary, and pericytes embedded in the capillary basement membrane.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] This system allows the passage of some small molecules by passive diffusion, as well as the selective and active transport of various nutrients, ions, organic anions, and molecules such as glucose and amino acids that are crucial to neural function.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The blood–brain barrier restricts the passage of pathogens, the diffusion of solutes in the blood, and large or hydrophilic molecules into the cerebrospinal fluid, while allowing the diffusion of hydrophobic molecules (O2, CO2, hormones) and small non-polar molecules.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Cells of the barrier actively transport metabolic products such as glucose across the barrier using specific transport proteins.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The barrier also restricts the passage of peripheral immune factors, like signaling molecules, antibodies, and immune cells, into the central nervous system, thus insulating the brain from damage due to peripheral immune events.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Specialized brain structures participating in sensory and secretory integration within brain neural circuits—the circumventricular organs and choroid plexus—have in contrast highly permeable capillaries.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The BBB results from the selectivity of the tight junctions between the endothelial cells of brain capillaries, restricting the passage of solutes.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] At the interface between blood and the brain, endothelial cells are adjoined continuously by these tight junctions, which are composed of smaller subunits of transmembrane proteins, such as occludin, claudins (such as Claudin-5), junctional adhesion molecule (such as JAM-A).
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Each of these tight junction proteins is stabilized to the endothelial cell membrane by another protein complex that includes scaffolding proteins such as tight junction protein 1 (ZO1) and associated proteins.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The BBB is composed of endothelial cells restricting passage of substances from the blood more selectively than endothelial cells of capillaries elsewhere in the body.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Astrocyte cell projections called astrocytic feet (also known as "glia limitans") surround the endothelial cells of the BBB, providing biochemical support to those cells.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The BBB is distinct from the quite similar blood-cerebrospinal fluid barrier, which is a function of the choroidal cells of the choroid plexus, and from the blood-retinal barrier, which can be considered a part of the whole realm of such barriers.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Not all vessels in the human brain exhibit BBB properties.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Some examples of this include the circumventricular organs, the roof of the third and fourth ventricles, capillaries in the pineal gland on the roof of the diencephalon and the pineal gland.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The BBB appears to be functional by the time of birth.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] P-glycoprotein, a transporter, exists already in the embryonal endothelium.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Measurement of brain uptake of various blood-borne solutes showed that newborn endothelial cells were functionally similar to those in adults, indicating that a selective BBB is operative at birth.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The blood–brain barrier acts effectively to protect brain tissue from circulating pathogens and other potentially toxic substances.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Accordingly, blood-borne infections of the brain are rare.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Infections of the brain that do occur are often difficult to treat.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Antibodies are too large to cross the blood–brain barrier, and only certain antibiotics are able to pass.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] In some cases, a drug has to be administered directly into the cerebrospinal fluid where it can enter the brain by crossing the blood-cerebrospinal fluid barrier.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Circumventricular organs (CVOs) are individual structures located adjacent to the fourth ventricle or third ventricle in the brain, and are characterized by dense capillary beds with permeable endothelial cells unlike those of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Included among CVOs having highly permeable capillaries are the area postrema, subfornical organ, vascular organ of the lamina terminalis, median eminence, pineal gland, and three lobes of the pituitary gland.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Consequently, the CVO permeable capillaries are the point of bidirectional blood–brain communication for neuroendocrine function.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The border zones between brain tissue "behind" the blood–brain barrier and zones "open" to blood signals in certain CVOs contain specialized hybrid capillaries that are leakier than typical brain capillaries, but not as permeable as CVO capillaries.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Such zones exist at the border of the area postrema—nucleus tractus solitarii (NTS), and median eminence—hypothalamic arcuate nucleus.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] These zones appear to function as rapid transit regions for brain structures involved in diverse neural circuits—like the NTS and arcuate nucleus—to receive blood signals which are then transmitted into neural output.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The blood–brain barrier is formed by the brain capillary endothelium and excludes from the brain 100% of large-molecule neurotherapeutics and more than 98% of all small-molecule drugs.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Overcoming the difficulty of delivering therapeutic agents to specific regions of the brain presents a major challenge to treatment of most brain disorders.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] In its neuroprotective role, the blood–brain barrier functions to hinder the delivery of many potentially important diagnostic and therapeutic agents to the brain.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Therapeutic molecules and antibodies that might otherwise be effective in diagnosis and therapy do not cross the BBB in adequate amounts to be clinically effective.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] To overcome this problem some peptides able to naturally cross the BBB have been widely investigated as a drug delivery system.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Mechanisms for drug targeting in the brain involve going either "through" or "behind" the BBB.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Modalities for drug delivery to the brain in unit doses through the BBB entail its disruption by osmotic means, or biochemically by the use of vasoactive substances, such as bradykinin, or even by localized exposure to high-intensity focused ultrasound (HIFU).
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Some studies have shown that vectors targeting BBB transporters, such as the transferrin receptor, have been found to remain entrapped in brain endothelial cells of capillaries, instead of being ferried across the BBB into the targeted area.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The brain can be targeted non-invasively via the nasal passage.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] However, these methods are less efficient to deliver drugs as they are indirect methods.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Nanotechnology is under preliminary research for its potential to facilitate the transfer of drugs across the BBB.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Capillary endothelial cells and associated pericytes may be abnormal in tumors and the blood–brain barrier may not always be intact in brain tumors.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Other factors, such as astrocytes, may contribute to the resistance of brain tumors to therapy using nanoparticles.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Fat-soluble molecules less than 400 daltons in mass can freely diffuse past the BBB through lipid-mediated passive diffusion.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The blood–brain barrier may become damaged in certain neurological diseases, as indicated by neuroimaging studies of Alzheimer's disease, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, epilepsy, hemorrhagic stroke, ischemic stroke, and brain trauma, and in systemic diseases, such as liver failure.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] However, in many neurodegenerative diseases, the exact cause and pathology remains unknown.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] An 1898 study observed that low-concentration "bile salts" failed to affect behavior when injected into the blood of animals.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Thus, in theory, the salts failed to enter the brain.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Two years later, Max Lewandowsky may have been the first to coin the term "blood–brain barrier" in 1900, referring to the hypothesized semipermeable membrane.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] There is some debate over the creation of the term *blood–brain barrier* as it is often attributed to Lewandowsky, but it does not appear in his papers.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] The creator of the term may have been Lina Stern.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Stern was a Russian scientist who published her work in Russian and French.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] Due to the language barrier between her publications and English-speaking scientists, this could have made her work a lesser-known origin of the term.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] All the while, bacteriologist Paul Ehrlich was studying staining, a procedure that is used in many microscopy studies to make fine biological structures visible using chemical dyes.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] As Ehrlich injected some of these dyes (notably the aniline dyes that were then widely used), the dye stained all of the organs of some kinds of animals except for their brains.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] At that time, Ehrlich attributed this lack of staining to the brain simply not picking up as much of the dye.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] However, in a later experiment in 1913, Edwin Goldmann (one of Ehrlich's students) injected the dye directly into the cerebrospinal fluid of animal brains.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] He found then the brains did become dyed, but the rest of the body did not, demonstrating the existence of a compartmentalization between the two.
[src:admet-prediction/blood-brain-barrier] At that time, it was thought that the blood vessels themselves were responsible for the barrier, since no obvious membrane could be found.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] P450s are, in general, the terminal oxidase enzymes in electron transfer chains, broadly categorized as P450-containing systems.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The term "P450" is derived from the spectrophotometric peak at the wavelength of the absorption maximum of the enzyme (450 nm) when it is in the reduced state and complexed with carbon monoxide.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Most P450s require a protein partner to deliver one or more electrons to reduce the iron (and eventually molecular oxygen).
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Genes encoding P450 enzymes, and the enzymes themselves, are designated with the root symbol **CYP** for the superfamily, followed by a number indicating the gene family, a capital letter indicating the subfamily, and another numeral for the individual gene.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The convention is to *italicize* the name when referring to the gene.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] For example, *CYP2E1* is the gene that encodes the enzyme CYP2E1—one of the enzymes involved in paracetamol (acetaminophen) metabolism.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The **CYP** nomenclature is the official naming convention, although occasionally **CYP450** or **CYP450** is used synonymously.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] These names should never be used as according to the nomenclature convention (as they denote a P450 in family number 450).
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] However, some gene or enzyme names for P450s are also referred to by historical names (e.g.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] P450BM3 for CYP102A1) or functional names, denoting the catalytic activity and the name of the compound used as substrate.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Examples include CYP5A1, thromboxane A2 synthase, abbreviated to TBXAS1 (thromboxane A2 synthase 1), and CYP51A1, lanosterol 14-α-demethylase, sometimes unofficially abbreviated to LDM according to its substrate (lanosterol) and activity (demethylation).
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The nomenclature guidelines suggest that members of new CYP families share at least 40% amino-acid identity, while members of subfamilies must share at least 55% amino-acid identity.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Nomenclature committees assign and track both base gene names (Cytochrome P450 Homepage Archived 2010-06-27 at the Wayback Machine) and allele names (CYP Allele Nomenclature Committee).
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] These similarity-based groupings are frequently recovered in phylogenetic analyses and members generally share features in their catalytic activities.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Sometimes the suggested similarity thresholds do not exactly match what phylogenetic patterns show (e.g. a new member that is close to a family but only 39% identical), causing what is known as "family creep" as the similarity threshold is reduced, or the occasional split of families.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The taxonomic group blocks are defined for CYP1001–CYP69999 by stretching the taxonomic blocks defined for CYP101–999.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The reservations defined under these groups are not stretched.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] As of April 2026, the most complete database is the P450 Atlas (version 1.3.0) covering 11068 families, 26037 subfamilies, 79577 ortholog groups and 164068 example sequences of ortholog groups.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Comparison between many P450 enzymes of different families give rise to the concept of *clans*, evolutionary grouping of families.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The exact similarity cut-off is poorly defined, but it is generally understood that it should derive from a few first-diverging nodes of a phylogenetic tree.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Some clans only have one family while others are highly diversified with many families within (e.g.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Tracking the emergence of clans and families across many taxonomic groups paints a vivid picture of the evolution of metabolic capabilities.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The active site of cytochrome P450 contains a heme-iron center.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The iron is tethered to the protein via a cysteine thiolate ligand.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] This cysteine and several flanking residues are highly conserved in known P450s, and have the formal PROSITE signature consensus pattern [FW] - [SGNH] - x - [GD] - {F} - [RKHPT] - {P} - C - [LIVMFAP] - [GAD].
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Substrate binding induces electron transfer from NAD(P)H via cytochrome P450 reductase or another associated reductase, converting Fe(III) to Fe(II).
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Molecular oxygen binds to the resulting ferrous heme center at the distal axial coordination position, initially giving a dioxygen adduct similar to oxy-myoglobin.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] A second electron is transferred, from either cytochrome P450 reductase, ferredoxins, or cytochrome b5, reducing the Fe-O2 adduct to give a short-lived peroxo state.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The peroxo group formed in step 4 is rapidly protonated twice, releasing one molecule of water and forming the highly reactive species referred to as **P450 Compound 1** (or just Compound I).
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] This highly reactive intermediate was isolated in 2010, P450 Compound 1 is an iron(IV) oxo (or ferryl) species with an additional oxidizing equivalent delocalized over the porphyrin and thiolate ligands.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Evidence for the alternative perferryl iron(V)-oxo is lacking.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Depending on the substrate and enzyme involved, P450 enzymes can catalyze any of a wide variety of reactions.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] A hypothetical hydroxylation is illustrated.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] After the hydroxylated product has been released from the active site, the enzyme returns to its original state, with a water molecule returning to occupy the distal coordination position of the iron nucleus.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] An alternative route for mono-oxygenation is via the "peroxide shunt" (path "S" in figure).
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] This pathway entails oxidation of the ferric-substrate complex with oxygen-atom donors such as peroxides and hypochlorites.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] A hypothetical peroxide "XOOH" is shown in the diagram.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Mechanistic details, including the oxygen rebound mechanism, have been investigated with synthetic analogues, consisting of iron oxo heme complexes.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Binding of substrate is reflected in the spectral properties of the enzyme, with an increase in absorbance at 390 nm and a decrease at 420 nm.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] This can be measured by difference spectroscopies and is referred to as the "type I" difference spectrum (see inset graph in figure).
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Some substrates cause an opposite change in spectral properties, a "reverse type I" spectrum, by processes that are as yet unclear.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Inhibitors and certain substrates that bind directly to the heme iron give rise to the type II difference spectrum, with a maximum at 430 nm and a minimum at 390 nm (see inset graph in figure).
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] If no reducing equivalents are available, this complex may remain stable, allowing the degree of binding to be determined from absorbance measurements *in vitro* C: If carbon monoxide (CO) binds to reduced P450, the catalytic cycle is interrupted.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] This reaction yields the classic CO difference spectrum with a maximum at 450 nm.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] However, the interruptive and inhibitory effects of CO varies upon different CYPs such that the CYP3A family is relatively less affected.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The heme in cytochrome P450 binds to a conserved sequence: `FxxGxRxCxG`, where "x" denotes some variant amino acid.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The cysteine (C) binds Fe and arginine (R), forming strong electrostatic interactions with negatively charged side chains of the heme.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] The glycine (G) residues within the conserved sequence are essential, as their small structure enables surrounding alpha helices to remain in place without interacting with a variant amino acid.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Many hydroxylation reactions (insertion of hydroxyl groups) use CYP enzymes, but many other hydroxylases exist.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Alpha-ketoglutarate-dependent hydroxylases also rely on an Fe=O intermediate but lack hemes.
[src:admet-prediction/cytochrome-p450] Methane monooxygenase, which converts methane to methanol, are non-heme iron-and iron-copper-based enzymes.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] The liver plays a central role in transforming and clearing chemicals and is susceptible to the toxicity from these agents.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Certain medicinal agents when taken in overdoses (e.g. paracetamol, sometimes called acetaminophen), and sometimes even when introduced within therapeutic ranges (e.g. halothane), may injure the organ.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Other chemical agents, such as those used in laboratories and industries, natural chemicals (e.g., alpha-amanitin), and herbal remedies (two prominent examples being kava, though the causal mechanism is unknown, and comfrey, through pyrrolizidine alkaloid content) can also induce hepatotoxicity.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Chemicals that cause liver injury are called hepatotoxins.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] More than 900 drugs have been implicated in causing liver injury (see LiverTox, external link, below) and it is the most common reason for a drug to be withdrawn from the market.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Hepatotoxicity and drug-induced liver injury also account for a substantial number of compound failures, highlighting the need for toxicity prediction models (e.g.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] DTI), and drug screening assays, such as stem cell-derived hepatocyte-like cells, that are capable of detecting toxicity early in the drug development process.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Chemicals often cause subclinical injury to the liver, which manifests only as abnormal liver enzyme tests.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Drug-induced liver injury is responsible for 5% of all hospital admissions and 50% of all acute liver failures.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Adverse drug reactions are classified as type A (intrinsic or pharmacological) or type B (idiosyncratic).
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Type A drug reaction accounts for 80% of all toxicities.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Drugs or toxins that have a pharmacological (type A) hepatotoxicity are those that have *predictable* dose-response curves (higher concentrations cause more liver damage) and well characterized mechanisms of toxicity, such as directly damaging liver tissue or blocking a metabolic process.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] As in the case of paracetamol overdose, this type of injury occurs shortly after some threshold for toxicity is reached.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Carbon tetrachloride is commonly used to induce acute type A liver injury in animal models.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Idiosyncratic (type B) injury occurs without warning, when agents cause *non-predictable* hepatotoxicity in susceptible individuals, which is not related to dose and has a variable latency period.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] This type of injury does not have a clear dose-response nor temporal relationship, and most often does not have predictive models.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Idiosyncratic hepatotoxicity has led to the withdrawal of several drugs from market even after rigorous clinical testing as part of the FDA approval process; Troglitazone (Rezulin) and trovafloxacin (Trovan) are two prime examples of idiosyncratic hepatotoxins pulled from market.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] The herb kava has caused a number of cases of idiosyncratic liver injury, ranging everywhere from asymptomatic to fatal.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Oral use of the antifungal ketoconazole has been associated with hepatic toxicity, including some fatalities; however, such effects appear to be limited to doses taken over a period longer than 7 days.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Paracetamol also known as acetaminophen, and by the brand names of Tylenol and Panadol, is usually well-tolerated in prescribed dose, but overdose is the most common cause of drug-induced liver disease and acute liver failure worldwide.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Damage to the liver is not due to the drug itself but to a toxic metabolite (*N*-acetyl-*p*-benzoquinone imine (NAPQI)) produced by cytochrome P-450 enzymes in the liver.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] In normal circumstances, this metabolite is detoxified by conjugating with glutathione in phase 2 reaction.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] In an overdose, a large amount of NAPQI is generated, which overwhelms the detoxification process and leads to liver cell damage.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Nitric oxide also plays a role in inducing toxicity.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] The risk of liver injury is influenced by several factors including the dose ingested, concurrent alcohol or other drug intake, interval between ingestion and antidote, etc.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] The dose toxic to the liver is quite variable from person to person and is often thought to be lower in chronic alcoholics.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Measurement of blood level is important in assessing prognosis, higher levels predicting a worse prognosis.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Administration of Acetylcysteine, a precursor of glutathione, can limit the severity of the liver damage by capturing the toxic NAPQI.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Those that develop acute liver failure can still recover spontaneously, but may require transplantation if poor prognostic signs such as encephalopathy or coagulopathy is present (see King's College Criteria).
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Although individual analgesics rarely induce liver damage due to their widespread use, NSAIDs have emerged as a major group of drugs exhibiting hepatotoxicity.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Both dose-dependent and idiosyncratic reactions have been documented.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Aspirin and phenylbutazone are associated with intrinsic hepatotoxicity; idiosyncratic reaction has been associated with ibuprofen, sulindac, phenylbutazone, piroxicam, diclofenac and indomethacin.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Glucocorticoids are so named due to their effect on the carbohydrate mechanism.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] They promote glycogen storage in the liver.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] An enlarged liver is a rare side-effect of long-term steroid use in children.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] The classical effect of prolonged use both in adult and paediatric population is steatosis.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Isoniazide (INH) is one of the most commonly used drugs for tuberculosis; it is associated with mild elevation of liver enzymes in up to 20% of patients and severe hepatotoxicity in 1-2% of patients.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] There are also cases where other hydrazine derivative drugs, such as the MAOI antidepressant iproniazid, are associated with liver damage.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Phenelzine has been associated with abnormal liver tests.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Toxic effects can develop from antibiotics, such as amoxicillin/clavulanic acid.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Examples include alpha-Amanitin containing mushrooms, kava, and aflatoxin producing molds.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Pyrrolizidine alkaloids, which occur in some plants, can be toxic.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Green tea extract is a growing cause of liver failure due to its inclusion in more products.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Examples include: Ackee fruit, Bajiaolian, Camphor, Copaltra, Cycasin, Garcinia, Kava leaves, pyrrolizidine alkaloids, Horse chestnut leaves, Valerian, Comfrey.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Chinese herbal remedies: Jin Bu Huan, Ephedra, Shou Wu Pian, Bai Xian Pi.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Examples include arsenic, carbon tetrachloride, and vinyl chloride.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Drugs continue to be taken off the market due to late discovery of hepatotoxicity.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Due to its unique metabolism and close relationship with the gastrointestinal tract, the liver is susceptible to injury from drugs and other substances.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] 75% of blood coming to the liver arrives directly from gastrointestinal organs and the spleen via portal veins that bring drugs and xenobiotics in near-undiluted form.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Several mechanisms are responsible for either inducing hepatic injury or worsening the damage process.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Many chemicals damage mitochondria, an intracellular organelle that produces energy.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Its dysfunction releases excessive amount of oxidants that, in turn, injure hepatic cells.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Activation of some enzymes in the cytochrome P-450 system such as CYP2E1 also lead to oxidative stress.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Injury to hepatocyte and bile duct cells lead to accumulation of bile acid inside the liver.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Non-parenchymal cells such as Kupffer cells, collagen-producing stellate cells, and leukocytes (i.e. neutrophil and monocyte) also have a role in the mechanism.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] The human body subjects most, but not all, compounds to various chemical processes (i.e. metabolism) to make them suitable for elimination.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] This involves chemical transformations to (a) reduce fat solubility and (b) to change biological activity.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] The central role played by liver in the clearance and transformation of chemicals makes it susceptible to drug-induced injury.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Drug metabolism is usually divided into two phases: *phase 1* and *phase 2*.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Phase 1 reaction is generally speaking to prepare a drug for phase 2.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] However, many compounds can be metabolized by phase 2 directly or be excreted without any phase 2 reactions occurring.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Phase 1 reaction involves oxidation, reduction, hydrolysis, hydration and many other rare chemical reactions.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] These processes tend to increase water solubility of the drug and can generate metabolites that are more chemically active and/or potentially toxic.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Most of phase 2 reactions take place in cytosol and involve conjugation with endogenous compounds via transferase enzymes.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Phase 1 are typically more suitable for elimination.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] A group of enzymes located in the endoplasmic reticulum, known as cytochrome P-450, is the most important family of metabolizing enzymes in the liver.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Cytochrome P-450 is not a single enzyme, but rather consists of a closely related family of 50 isoforms; six of them metabolize 90% of drugs.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] There is a tremendous diversity of individual P-450 gene products, and this heterogeneity allows the liver to perform oxidation on a vast array of chemicals (including most drugs) in phase 1.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Each of the P-450 proteins is unique and accounts (to some extent) for the variation in drug metabolism between individuals.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Genetic variations (polymorphism) in P-450 metabolism should be considered when patients exhibit unusual sensitivity or resistance to drug effects at normal doses.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Such polymorphism is also responsible for variable drug response among patients of differing ethnic backgrounds.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Many substances can influence the P-450 enzyme mechanism.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Drugs interact with the enzyme family in several ways.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Drugs that modify cytochrome P-450 enzyme are referred to as either inhibitors or inducers.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Enzyme inhibitors block the metabolic activity of one or several P-450 enzymes.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] On the other hand, inducers increase P-450 activity by increasing enzyme production, or, in the case of CYP2E1, preventing degradation in the proteasome.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] There is usually a delay before enzyme activity increases.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Some drugs may share the same P-450 specificity and thus competitively block their biotransformation.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] This may lead to accumulation of drugs metabolized by the enzyme.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] This type of drug interaction may also reduce the rate of generation of toxic metabolites.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Chemicals produce a wide variety of clinical and pathological hepatic injury.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Biochemical markers (e.g. alanine transferase, alkaline phosphatase and bilirubin) are often used to indicate liver damage.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Liver injury is defined as a rise in either (a) ALT level more than three times of upper limit of normal (ULN), (b) ALP level more than twice ULN, or (c) total bilirubin level more than twice ULN when associated with increased ALT or ALP.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Liver damage is further characterized into hepatocellular (predominantly initial Alanine transferase elevation) and cholestatic (initial alkaline phosphatase rise) types.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] However they are not mutually exclusive and mixed types of injuries are often encountered.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Specific histo-pathological patterns of liver injury from drug-induced damage are discussed below.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] This is the most common type of drug-induced liver cell necrosis where the injury is largely confined to a particular zone of the liver lobule.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] It may manifest as a very high level of ALT and severe disturbance of liver function leading to acute liver failure.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] In this pattern, hepatocellular necrosis is associated with infiltration of inflammatory cells.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] There can be three types of drug-induced hepatitis.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] (A) viral hepatitis is the most common, where histological features are similar to acute viral hepatitis.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] (B) in focal or non-specific hepatitis, scattered foci of cell necrosis may accompany lymphocytic infiltration.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] (C) chronic hepatitis is very similar to autoimmune hepatitis clinically, serologically, and histologically.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Liver injury leads to impairment of bile flow and cases are predominated by itching and jaundice.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Histology may show inflammation (cholestatic hepatitis) or it can be bland (without any parenchymal inflammation).
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] On rare occasions, it can produce features similar to primary biliary cirrhosis due to progressive destruction of small bile ducts (vanishing duct syndrome).
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Hepatotoxicity may manifest as triglyceride accumulation, which leads to either small-droplet (microvesicular) or large-droplet (macrovesicular) fatty liver.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Drug-induced hepatic granulomas are usually associated with granulomas in other tissues and patients typically have features of systemic vasculitis and hypersensitivity.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] More than 50 drugs have been implicated.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] These result from injury to the vascular endothelium.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Neoplasms have been described with prolonged exposure to some medications or toxins.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Hepatocellular carcinoma, angiosarcoma, and liver adenomas are the ones usually reported.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] This remains a challenge in clinical practice due to a lack of reliable markers.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Many other conditions lead to similar clinical as well as pathological pictures.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] To diagnose hepatotoxicity, a causal relationship between the use of the toxin or drug and subsequent liver damage has to be established, but might be difficult, especially when idiosyncratic reaction is suspected.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Simultaneous use of multiple drugs may add to the complexity.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] As in acetaminophen toxicity, well established, dose-dependent, pharmacological hepatotoxicity is easier to spot.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Several clinical scales such as CIOMS/RUCAM scale and Maria and Victorino criteria have been proposed to establish causal relationship between offending drug and liver damage.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] CIOMS/RUCAM scale involves a scoring system that categorizes the suspicion into "definite or highly probable" (score > 8), "probable" (score 6–8), "possible" (score 3–5), "unlikely" (score 1–2) and "excluded" (score ≤ 0).
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] In clinical practice, physicians put more emphasis on the presence or absence of similarity between the biochemical profile of the patient and known biochemical profile of the suspected toxicity (e.g., cholestatic damage in amoxycillin-clauvonic acid ).
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] In most cases, liver function will return to normal if the offending drug is stopped early.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Additionally, the patient may require supportive treatment.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] In acetaminophen toxicity, however, the initial insult can be fatal.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Fulminant hepatic failure from drug-induced hepatotoxicity may require liver transplantation.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] In the past, glucocorticoids in allergic features and ursodeoxycholic acid in cholestatic cases had been used, but there is no good evidence to support their effectiveness.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] An elevation in serum bilirubin level of more than 2 times ULN with associated transaminase rise indicates severe hepatotoxicity and is likely to lead to mortality in 10% to 15% of patients, especially if the offending drug is not stopped (Hy's Law).
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] This is because it requires significant damage to the liver to impair bilirubin excretion, hence minor impairment (in the absence of biliary obstruction or Gilbert syndrome) would not lead to jaundice.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] Other poor predictors of outcome are old age, female sex, high AST.
[src:admet-prediction/hepatotoxicity] The following therapeutic drugs were withdrawn from the market primarily because of hepatotoxicity: Troglitazone, bromfenac, trovafloxacin, ebrotidine, nimesulide, nefazodone, ximelagatran and pemoline.
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] Roughly speaking, the $V_{D}$ , as a property of a drug, measures the degree to which it is distributed in body tissue rather than the blood plasma.
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] Drug properties which cause high $V_{D}$ include high lipid solubility (non-polarity), low rates of ionization, or low plasma protein binding capabilities.
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] Disease states which increase $V_{D}$ include kidney failure (due to fluid retention) and liver failure (due to altered body fluid and plasma protein binding).
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] Conversely, dehydration may decrease $V_{D}$ .
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] The initial volume of distribution describes blood concentrations prior to attaining the apparent volume of distribution and uses the same formula.
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] Suppose one administers an *amount of drug* D intravascularly, then measures the *drug concentration in blood* $C_{0}$ (assuming enough time has elapsed for the drug to distribute, but not enough time for elimination).
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] If the drug remains entirely intravascularly, $V_{D}$ will be identical to the blood volume $V_{blood}$ .
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] However, if a drug diffuses out of the intravascular space into the tissues or interstitium, the measured concentration will be lower-than-expected compared to a hypothetical intravascular-only drug.
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] Therefore, $V_{D}>V_{blood}$ , with a higher $V_{D}$ value corresponding to a greater tendency for the drug to exit the intravascular space.
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] One clinical utility is that the dose required D to achieve a target plasma concentration $C_{0}$ can be determined if the $V_{D}$ for that drug is known.
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] The $V_{D}$ is **not** a physiological value; it is more a reflection of how a drug will distribute throughout the body depending on several physicochemical properties such as solubility, charge, size, etc.
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] The unit for $V_{D}$ may be reported extensively in litres (for a patient of given weight), or intensively as litres-per-kilogram.
[src:admet-prediction/volume-of-distribution] For example, chloroquine has much greater affinity for body fat than blood, resulting in a $V_{D}\approx 250L/kg$ compared to $V_{blood}\approx 0.08L/kg$ .
